$lang['When it comes to decoding Hexadecimal, there are a few things you need to know. First, just like the decimal system, the hexadecimal system has 10 symbols (0-9) that represent numbers. However, in hexadecimal, these digits have values that are twice as large as their counterparts in the decimal system. So, while the number “10” is represented by the symbol “A” in hexadecimal, it would be equal to “10” in the decimal system.'] = 'Kana zvasvika pakudhirodha Hexadecimal, pane zvinhu zvishoma zvaunofanira kuziva. Chekutanga, kungofanana nedecimal system, iyo hexadecimal system ine gumi zviratidzo (0-9) inomiririra nhamba. Zvisineyi, muhexadecimal, manhamba aya ane makoshero akakura zvakapetwa kaviri pane mamwewo ari mudecimal system. Saka, nepo nhamba &quot;10&quot; ichimiririrwa nechiratidzo &quot;A&quot; muhexadecimal, inenge yakaenzana ne &quot;10&quot; mudecimal system.';
$lang['Similarly, after reaching 9 in Hexadecimal (represented by “F”), we start counting again at 10 (“10”). This pattern continues until we reach 15 (“1F”), at which point we reset back to 0 and begin counting again at 16 (“20”). This might sound confusing at first, but with a little practice, it will become second nature!'] = 'Saizvozvowo, mushure mokunge tasvika 9 muHexadecimal (inomiririrwa ne &quot;F&quot;), tinotanga kuverenga zvakare pa10 (&quot;10&quot;). Patani iyi inoenderera mberi kusvika tasvika 15 (&quot;1F&quot;), panguva iyoyo tinodzokera ku0 totanga kuverenga zvakare pa16 (&quot;20&quot;). Izvi zvingaita sezvisinganzwisisike pakutanga, asi nekuita zvishoma, zvinova hunhu hwechipiri!';
